body:
Right now, when there's a memory out-of-bound access, you get a message like this:

```
tb: ./FirEngine.cpp:480: virtual bool cxxrtl_design::p_FirEngine::eval(): Assertion `tmp_2.valid && "out of bounds write"' failed.
```

When you track this down in the .cpp file, you get something like this:

```verilog
	// \src: ../../spinal/FirEngine.v:0.0-0.0
	// cell $memwr$\u_mem$../../spinal/FirEngine.v:0$87
	auto tmp_2 = memory_index(i_memwr_24__5c_u__mem_24__2e__2e__2f__2e__2e__2f_spinal_2f_FirEngine_2e_v_3a_199_24_1__ADDR.curr, 0, 186);
	CXXRTL_ASSERT(tmp_2.valid && "out of bounds write");
	if (tmp_2.valid) {
		memory_p_u__mem.update(tmp_2.index, i_memwr_24__5c_u__mem_24__2e__2e__2f__2e__2e__2f_spinal_2f_FirEngine_2e_v_3a_199_24_1__DATA.curr, i_memwr_24__5c_u__mem_24__2e__2e__2f__2e__2e__2f_spinal_2f_FirEngine_2e_v_3a_199_24_1__EN.curr, 87);
	}
```

It's not very descriptive, and the signals that matter are also not debug_items, so you can't dump them in a VCD file.

This needs better debug options, such as a print message that indicates the hierarchical name of the RAM, which address is being read or written, and which value is being written.

debug_items would be useful as well.

